docs.abstract: The president blames Michael Atkinson, whom he appointed, for finding the anonymous whistle-blower’s complaint on his interactions with Ukraine to be credible.
docs.snippet: The president blames Michael Atkinson, whom he appointed, for finding the anonymous whistle-blower’s complaint on his interactions with Ukraine to be credible.
docs.lead_paragraph: President Trump has discussed dismissing the intelligence community’s inspector general, Michael Atkinson, because Mr. Atkinson reported a whistle-blower’s complaint about Mr. Trump’s interactions with Ukraine to Congress after concluding it was credible, according to four people familiar with the discussions.

headline.main: Trump Has Considered Firing Intelligence Community Inspector General
headline.print_headline: Trump Mulled Firing Official For Reporting Ukraine Call

docs.abstract: No Republicans and only two Democrats broke ranks, a sign that the inquiry is likely to remain a highly partisan affair.
docs.snippet: No Republicans and only two Democrats broke ranks, a sign that the inquiry is likely to remain a highly partisan affair.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When the Republican-led House voted in 1998 to begin an impeachment inquiry into President Bill Clinton, 31 Democrats sided with Republicans, and the White House breathed a sigh of relief that the number was not significantly larger. In today’s hyper-polarized Washington, defections of that magnitude on the question of impeachment would be considered a tsunami.

headline.main: What the Impeachment Vote Says About the Trump Inquiry’s Future
headline.print_headline: Few Defectors, and No Signs That Either Side Will Give an Inch

docs.abstract: A new batch of leaked emails illustrates the degree to which Mr. Miller used a think tank’s work to shape coverage at Breitbart News and policy at the White House.
docs.snippet: A new batch of leaked emails illustrates the degree to which Mr. Miller used a think tank’s work to shape coverage at Breitbart News and policy at the White House.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Stephen Miller, President Trump’s hard-line immigration adviser, has long relied on data produced by the Center for Immigration Studies, a right-leaning think tank, to shape policy at the White House. Shortly after Mr. Trump was elected, Mr. Miller became well-known in the West Wing for putting printouts of studies published by the group on the president’s desk.

headline.main: Emails Outline Anti-Immigration Group’s Connection to Stephen Miller
headline.print_headline: Using an Anti-Immigration Group’s Data, Miller Drove Breitbart Coverage
